TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rules Versus Discretion: The Productivity Consequences of Flexible Regulation
AU  - Majumdar, Sumit K.
AU  - Marcus, Alfred A.
Y1  - 2001/02/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069344
DO  - 10.5465/3069344
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 170
EP  - 179
VL  - 44
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Using data from electric utilities, this study shows that spending on well-designed regulations has a positive productivity impact but that spending on less well-designed regulations has a negative effect. Better-designed regulations are flexible and grant firms latitude on how to meet goals, allow them time to deploy new means to meet goals, and set ambitious goals that stretch them beyond current practices.
AB  - Using data from electric utilities, this study shows that spending on well-designed regulations has a positive productivity impact but that spending on less well-designed regulations has a negative effect. Better-designed regulations are flexible and grant firms latitude on how to meet goals, allow them time to deploy new means to meet goals, and set ambitious goals that stretch them beyond current practices.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069344
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069344
